  "prompt": "Can I use my debit card as credit card on Airbnb?",
  "response": "Yes, you can use your debit card on Airbnb as if it were a credit card, but there are a few important things to keep in mind:\n\n### 1. **Adding the Debit Card as a Payment Method**\n   - Airbnb accepts debit cards as long as they are Visa, MasterCard, American Express, or Discover.\n   - You can add your debit card to your Airbnb account in the same way you would add a credit card.\n\n### 2. **Authorization Holds**\n   - When you book a stay, Airbnb may place a temporary authorization hold on your debit card to ensure funds are available. This hold can tie up funds in your bank account until it\u2019s released, which can take a few days.\n\n### 3. **Refunds and Cancellations**\n   - If you cancel a booking, refunds may take longer to process with a debit card compared to a credit card, depending on your bank\u2019s policies.\n\n### 4. **Security and Fraud Protection**\n   - While debit cards offer some level of protection, credit cards generally provide stronger fraud protection and dispute resolution options. If you\u2019re concerned about security, using a credit card might be a better choice.\n\n### 5. **International Bookings**\n   - For international bookings, ensure your debit card is enabled for international transactions and check for any foreign transaction fees your bank may charge.\n\n### 6. **Partial Payments**\n   - If Airbnb offers a payment plan (like splitting the cost into multiple payments), this option is typically only available with credit cards, not debit cards.\n\n### 7. **Host Preferences**\n   - Some hosts or listings may require a credit card for booking, though this is not common. Always check the listing details or contact the host if unsure.\n\n### Steps to Use a Debit Card:\n   - Go to your Airbnb account settings.\n   - Navigate to **Payment Methods** and add your debit card.\n   - During checkout, select your debit card as the payment method.\n\nIf you don\u2019t have a credit card, using a debit card is a viable option, but be mindful of potential holds and slower refund processing.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
